From: stevev@miser.uoregon.edu (Steve VanDevender)
Subject: Re: How is Linux/X performance in 8MB?
Date: 4 Dec 93 20:47:18

I have a Linux box with 8M of memory and a 386DX40 and run X most
of the time.

I can confirm some of the other impressions that have already
been posted.  Performance is fine for normal tasks like shell
commands and editing with Emacs 19.  Things definitely slow down
when running compiles with GCC, but typically the compiles don't
swap much once the compilation has pushed enough things out of
memory.

XV uses a lot of memory, especially for large pictures, and can
be slow.  I am not doing a lot of image processing so I just use
XV to look at GIFs and JPEGs once in a while.

I am probably going to upgrade to 16 or 20M within the next month
or two (assuming that SIMM prices continue to drop back to
normal) but unless you are really impatient you will probably not
have much trouble with running X in 8M.  You may be pushing the
limits of 8M with your applications, though.

I am only gradually getting over the euphoria of having my own
Unix box and X workstation at home; probably when I upgrade my
system with 20M and a 486DX2/66 I will wonder how I got along
with what I have now.
--
Steve VanDevender       stevev@greylady.uoregon.edu
"Bipedalism--an unrecognized disease affecting over 99% of the population.
Symptoms include lack of traffic sense, slow rate of travel, and the
classic, easily recognized behavior known as walking."

