From: tdunbar@vtaix.cc.vt.edu (Thomas Dunbar)
Subject: Re: Linux IS well documented.
Date: 5 Dec 1993 05:00:32 GMT


markline@henson.cc.wwu.edu (Mark Line) writes:

>tdunbar@vtaix.cc.vt.edu (Thomas Dunbar) writes:
>
>>I frequently read that linux is not well documented. I disagree. I
>>don't refer to the man pages (tho they seem ok to me) nor even the docs
>>put out by the LDP (tho i think, for example, the Kernel Hacker's
>>Guide is nice). Rather:
>>
>> An operating system with source code is better documented than any
>>os without source code. Certainly, Linux could be better documented,
>>but the essential documentation is there.
>
>I've written many, many lines of C in my day but this attitude just
>makes me puke. There's only one community of computer experts -- taken
>as a whole, they have to somehow support everybody interested in using
>computers, not just other experts. It's like saying that the best

well, i did go overboard with "the" essential..there's certainly
other needed docs. i didnt mean only source was needed. but it 
is the most needed documentation, imo.

>documentation for a car is its design file. Not the easiest way to
>learn how to drive it, even if it could be done.

yes, i'd probably say that too. if you just want to drive it or
even do simple repairs, no docs are needed. or at any rate, nothing
specific to the particular car model. 

>I can only reiterate Magnus' proposal that the Linux Consortium is not
>targeted at hackers like you who read source instead of the man page.

i've never written a C program in my life and only read source when i
need to. metafont is the only language i claim to know, and little 
knowledge of that. but even as ignorant as i am about programming, i've
found programs (xdvi, tex) that had "bugs" that i could fix since the source
was available. 
 actually, i now read source when i dont need to..having it available,
one finds that one can find useful info browsing around mostly 
incomprehensible stuff. 
 in the language i use, i find Knuth's "The METAFONTbook" far, far
more useful than "METAFONT: The Program." Nonetheless, if only one
of the two books could exist, i'd certainly say the program book is
more important. 

>> btw, compiling linux with -Wall, the compiler gives few (no?)
>>warnings. i assume the same would be true for aix, ultrix, solaris?

>I just presented this question to some novice users I support. Their
>reply? "What's a compiler?"

the btw is short for "by the way" which means different topic. i don't
see any point at all in asking the `novice user' such a question. i 
was just wondering since -Wall shows many warnings with lots of
software, was the lack of warnings due to the rigors of kernel writing
or Linus's skill and care?

>I rest my case.

i also answer questions (on how to use windows and mac programs)
from users who don't know what a compiler is. in my experience,
they do not (and will not) read ANY documentation.  
 


