From: kender@executor (Daniel Garcia (system overlord))
Subject: Re: Linux Consortium
Date: 5 Dec 1993 06:36:16 GMT
Reply-To: kender@esu.edu

Slaving away in a dark room, andreas@knobel.knirsch.de (Andreas Klemm) produced:
>
>My $0.02: Forget about it. Create a mailing list where you people
>can recommend each other this or that distributions ...
>

One problem here, not every single person in the world has access to email!
I personally like the idea of such a consortium, because it would give linux
a 'legitamacy' that would make it attractive to businesses, people who don't
have access to the net, and therefor can't get all the free and PD info from
the newsgroups and the like about linux, etc... etc...

The other alternative, is to let linux remain an OS for the experienced, and
only allow (or support, or whatever) people who know what they are doing, 
or have the resources/time/ability to learn, use it.  While I wouldn't have
a problem with that as well, that would keep linux in the position of
being a curiosity more than anything, something people will look at and say
'that's nice'.  Our school was looking at a free *nix OS for a while for
some of our machines, and decided to go with NetBSD, because of it's connection
w/BSD, they felt that gave it a better 'reputation' etc...

>This is a drawback for all those people who produce good quality
>packages .. to be "flamed" afterwards not to be user friendly '-)

So, then my suggestion to the LC, 'rate' packages, as being suitable for
delphi users, suitable for novices, suitable for experts, suitable for hackers,
suitable for S&M enthusiasts, whatever...  

>
>Really: forget about your "important organisation" :-( 

Why are you so afraid of this organization?

>Nerved

Me too, but that comes from too much caffine in my system ;)

D

